5000|$|CIN is {{calculated}} by measurements recorded electronically by a Rawinsonde (weather balloon) which carries devices which measure weather parameters, such as air temperature and pressure. A single value for CIN {{is calculated}} from one balloon ascent {{by use of}} the equation below. The z-bottom and z-top limits of integration in the equation represent the bottom and top altitudes (in meters) of a single CIN layer, [...] is the <b>virtual</b> <b>temperature</b> of the specific parcel and [...] is the <b>virtual</b> <b>temperature</b> of the environment. In many cases, the z-bottom value is {{the ground and the}} z-top value is the LFC. CIN is an energy per unit mass and the units of measurement are joules per kilogram (J/kg). CIN is expressed as a negative energy value. CIN values greater than 200 J/kg are sufficient to prevent convection in the atmosphere.|$|E
